<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF107-987-100  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 987 100.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Telecommunications  Dec 1989 v23 n12 p15(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Columbus Day virus proves a &quot;no show&quot; but others lurking.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Emigh, Jacqueline.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The much-publicized Columbus Day computer virus turned out to be afalse alarm but the Computer Virus Industry Association warns ofmore lethal epidemics.andP;  Every Fortune 500 company has beenreported to have been infected at least once.andP;  HEPNET, theDepartment of Energy's high energy physics network, and SPAN, NASA's Space Physics Analysis Network, have been assaulted by a viruscalled WANK or Worms Against Nuclear Killers.andP;  To prevent thepropagation of computer viruses, the US government has imposedstiff sanctions.andP;  Robert M. Morris Jr, author of the InternetWorm, was convicted by a federal grand jury.andP;  A bill has also beenintroduced that would make virus writing a federal crime.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer virusesComputer SystemsOffice AutomationCompaniesGovernment Agency.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>